nts and domestic companies to adjust to their foreign competitors. In International Differences in the Business Practices and Productivity of Firms, a distinguished group of contributors examines the phenomenon of widespread differences in managerial practices across firms, establishments within firms, and countries. This volume brings together eight studies that combine qualitative and quantitative insider analysis of business practices such as the use of teams, incentive pay, lean manufacturing, and quality control, revealing the elements that determine which practices are adopted and why. International Differences in the Business Practices and Productivity of Firms offers a much-needed model for measuring the productivity and performance of international firms in a fast-paced global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndustrial management. 0aIndustrial productivity. 0aInternational business enterprises. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aBartel, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlasi, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBushnell, James B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrea, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEriksson, Tor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Richard B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHelper, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIchniowski, Casey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleiner, Morris M., econtrib